Ambralivio

@Wally

I have seen machines that fail to allow booting from the Zalman for various reasons, some completely unknown. Somtimes Bios simply does not detect, but usb ports check out just fine. Some BIOS detects and identifies properly, but will not allow you to select it as a bootable device despite all bios options set to enable it. Some allow you to select, but simply will not boot. Some will allow you to select and boot but only if other obscure measures are taken such as only working on particular ports or removing all other optical drives etc. But never, ever have i seen it get detected as a additional USB hub in the BIOS or in an operating systems enumeration of attached devices. I have even seen it get detected as a different brand of optical, but in in those cases it still worked fine.

I'm not faulting the Zalman for any of this. As a fairly unique and still uncommon device it will find machines that will deal with it in quirky ways at times. That does not suprise me. It still works as intended in the vast majority of machines I've used it on but never has it failed due to being misidentified as a hub, or an optical drive behind a hub.
